    {
      "content": "Introduction to Spatial data",
      "pos": [
        1114,
        1142
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Spatial data describes the position and shape of objects in space.",
      "pos": [
        1144,
        1210
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In most applications, these correspond to objects on the earth, i.e. geospatial data.",
      "pos": [
        1211,
        1296
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Spatial data can be used to represent the location of a person, a place of interest, or the boundary of a city, or a lake.",
      "pos": [
        1297,
        1419
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Common use cases often involve proximity queries, for e.g., \"find all coffee shops near my current location\".",
      "pos": [
        1420,
        1529
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "GeoJSON",
      "pos": [
        1536,
        1543
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "DocumentDB supports indexing and querying of geospatial data that's represented using the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>GeoJSON specification<ept id=\"p1\">](http://geojson.org/geojson-spec.html)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        1544,
        1696
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "GeoJSON data structures are always valid JSON objects, so they can be stored and queried using DocumentDB without any specialized tools or libraries.",
      "pos": [
        1697,
        1846
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The DocumentDB SDKs provide helper classes and methods that make it easy to work with spatial data.",
      "pos": [
        1847,
        1946
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Points, Linestrings and Polygons",
      "pos": [
        1953,
        1985
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Point<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> denotes a single position in space.",
      "pos": [
        1986,
        2033
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In geospatial data, a point represents the exact location, which could be a street address of a grocery store, a kiosk, an automobile or a city.",
      "pos": [
        2034,
        2178
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A point is represented in GeoJSON (and DocumentDB) using its coordinate pair or longitude and latitude.",
      "pos": [
        2180,
        2283
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Here's an example JSON for a point.",
      "pos": [
        2284,
        2319
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Points in DocumentDB",
      "pos": [
        2323,
        2343
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> The GeoJSON specification specifies longitude first and latitude second.",
      "pos": [
        2420,
        2505
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Like in other mapping applications, longitude and latitude are angles and represented in terms of degrees.",
      "pos": [
        2506,
        2612
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Longitude values are measured from the Prime Meridian and are between -180 and 180.0 degrees, and latitude values are measured from the equator and are between -90.0 and 90.0 degrees.",
      "pos": [
        2613,
        2796
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "DocumentDB interprets coordinates as represented per the WGS-84 reference system.",
      "pos": [
        2802,
        2883
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Please see below for more details about coordinate reference systems.",
      "pos": [
        2884,
        2953
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This can be embedded in a DocumentDB document as shown in this example of a user profile containing location data:",
      "pos": [
        2955,
        3069
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Use Profile with Location stored in DocumentDB",
      "pos": [
        3073,
        3119
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition to points, GeoJSON also supports LineStrings and Polygons.",
      "pos": [
        3368,
        3438
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>LineStrings<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> represent a series of two or more points in space and the line segments that connect them.",
      "pos": [
        3439,
        3545
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In geospatial data, linestrings are commonly used to represent highways or rivers.",
      "pos": [
        3546,
        3628
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>polygon<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is a boundary of connected points that forms a closed LineString.",
      "pos": [
        3629,
        3708
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Polygons are commonly used to represent natural formations like lakes or political jurisdictions like cities and states.",
      "pos": [
        3709,
        3829
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Here's an example of a polygon in DocumentDB.",
      "pos": [
        3830,
        3875
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Polygons in DocumentDB",
      "pos": [
        3880,
        3902
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4101,
        4266
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> The GeoJSON specification requires that for valid polygons, the last coordinate pair provided should be the same as the first, to create a closed shape."
    },
    {
      "content": "Points within a polygon must be specified in counter-clockwise order.",
      "pos": [
        4270,
        4339
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A polygon specified in clockwise order represents the inverse of the region within it.",
      "pos": [
        4340,
        4426
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In addition to Point, LineString and Polygon, GeoJSON also specifies the representation for how to group multiple geospatial locations, as well as how to associate arbitrary properties with geolocation as a <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Feature<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        4428,
        4647
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Since these objects are valid JSON, they can all be stored and processed in DocumentDB.",
      "pos": [
        4648,
        4735
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Coordinate Reference Systems",
      "pos": [
        4741,
        4769
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Since the shape of the earth is irregular, coordinates of geospatial data is represented in many coordinate reference systems (CRS), each with their own frames of reference and units of measurement.",
      "pos": [
        4771,
        4969
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, the \"National Grid of Britain\" is a reference system is very accurate for the United Kingdom, but not outside it.",
      "pos": [
        4970,
        5096
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The most popular CRS in use today is the World Geodetic System  <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>WGS-84<ept id=\"p1\">](http://earth-info.nga.mil/GandG/wgs84/)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5099,
        5212
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "GPS devices, and many mapping services including Google Maps and Bing Maps APIs use WGS-84.",
      "pos": [
        5213,
        5304
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "DocumentDB supports indexing and querying of geospatial data using the WGS-84 CRS only.",
      "pos": [
        5305,
        5392
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Creating Documents with spatial data",
      "pos": [
        5398,
        5434
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When you create documents that contain GeoJSON values, they are automatically indexed with a spatial index in accordance to the indexing policy of the collection.",
      "pos": [
        5435,
        5597
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you're working with a DocumentDB SDK in a dynamically typed language like Python or Node.js, you must create valid GeoJSON.",
      "pos": [
        5598,
        5724
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create Document with Geospatial data in Node.js",
      "pos": [
        5728,
        5775
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you're working with the .NET (or Java) SDKs, you can use the new Point and Polygon classes within the Microsoft.Azure.Documents.Spatial namespace to embed location information within your application objects.",
      "pos": [
        6090,
        6301
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These classes help simplify the serialization and deserialization of spatial data into GeoJSON.",
      "pos": [
        6302,
        6397
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create Document with Geospatial data in .NET",
      "pos": [
        6401,
        6445
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you don't have the latitude and longitude information, but have the physical addresses or location name like city or country, you can look up the actual coordinates by using a geocoding service like Bing Maps REST Services.",
      "pos": [
        6935,
        7161
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Learn more about Bing Maps geocoding <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>here<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/ff701713.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
